I’ve been asked recently how I’ve been able to stay in the sport so long, which seems funny to me bc I still feel young 😂 The bottom line is I want to keep pushing myself. I also feel like my body gets back all my injury years … so really I’m like 27ish in running years🙃 The cool thing about running is while you compete with those around you, you’re really just trying to get the most out of yourself on that day. I love seeing how my body has adapted and gotten stronger these last few years. It’s a reminder that things take time and to be patient. The comparison game is hard but we’re all completely different so my biggest piece of advice is to not compare your timeline to anyone else’s ❤️ Here’s to continually striving to get the most our of ourselves 💪🏼

📹 @maxjrandolph ❤️

Have been feeling more like myself and getting back into the training groove 💪Had a solid workout with Max this AM which helped remind me that I do this bc I love running and pushing myself to find out how fast I can be. 

Its hard to swallow the failures in this sport but reminding myself that failure is a part of the sport. Failures can lead to growth and there’s no one in this sport who hasn’t dealt with failure. We can spend eternity reflecting on all the possible ‘what if’s’. Countless factors contribute to each race. And while it can be helpful to reflect and learn, sometimes it’s just not your day and it’s more helpful to shift your focus on what you can control; for me that’s getting back to work and continuing the consistency. Luckily, there’s always another race and I feel grateful knowing I have a great team around me AND I still believe in myself ✨All we can do is keep putting one foot in front of the other, work on getting better, and not dwell too much on why things didn’t go perfectly. Sometimes it just happens 🤷🏼‍♀️ 

#runner #running #failing #failingforward #controlthecontrollables #believe #goalgetter #process #progressnotperfection #workinprogress #havefun #passion

My main focus is on my mental health at the moment. I’m committing to focus on myself, my anxiety and depression 🫶🏻 AND not feel guilt or shame for feeling this way. This is something I’ve really struggled with over the years and a lot this last year. I get angry that my brain has the audacity to struggle when others have it so much worse. And I really don’t want to feel this way so I try my hardest to just will it away. But discarding my thoughts and invalidating these feelings (BC I have so much to be grateful for) starts a worse cycle. Honoring these feelings and knowing it’s OK, as well as talking to my therapist, working on my mindset, gratitude journaling, savoring the good moments, and feeling ok to not feel ok all the time is helping me find my happiness and confidence. Depression and anxiety look different on everyone. I debated posting this but working on being more open ❤️ Anyone else struggling I feel you and it’s ok 🫶🏻❤️

Happy Labor Day! Sharing one of my fave parts of my job today, food! I LOVE to eat 🍔🍕🥗🌯🍪 and food is fuel for your body and mind, whether you’re running or have an off day. I’ve had a few people reach out to ask about my nutrition so wanted to make a lil post about it 😊

Running your best means fueling enough. While I don’t count calories I make sure I eat all foods and enough food. I love sharing what I eat and while I don’t just live on ribs, sweets, and coffees, these are some of my favorite foods and there’s no need to cut them out!! 

I wanna share a few reasons why you should never skip a meal or try to restrict calories (also if you struggle I highly recommend consulting a dietician / nutritionist who can help you with specifics ❤️ @fueling_forward page is the best for info from an RD)

1️⃣ Energy: Food provides the energy you need to crush those long runs, workouts, and gym days. Making sure you eat plenty of carbies (these really are energy powerhouse), proteins, and fats (need all 3!) will keep your energy levels high! 

2️⃣Recovery: Food helps build and repair your muscles. Esp focus on getting in enough protein, like chicken, fish, and tofu in meals as well as protein shakes after sessions. This will help you recover and capitalize on those strength gains 🏋🏻‍♀️

3️⃣ Mental Side: Eating a well-balanced diet improves focus, concentration, and overall brain function. Eating well balanced meals that include nuts, seeds, and whole grains will keep your mental mojo at its peak!

Eating enough is essential for your success! There are no shortcuts in this sport and ensuring you fuel well in your teens and 20s helps you to stay healthy and have success in your 30s and beyond 🌟🏃‍♀️

Drop a comment below and let me know your favorite fueling foods! 🍽️ And tag your running buddies to spread the positivity and encourage them to eat enough too!

Consistency is 🔑 

I had years of only being healthy for half of the year and working myself into the ground those times I wasn’t hurt. While I may have had some good (even great) results it wasn’t sustainable and was both mentally and physically exhausting. I was always anticipating my next break down and hoping it came after the big competition. I still believe I have PRs in me and the only way for me to get there is to have consistency. There are no shortcuts in this sport; it takes time, hundreds of miles, and stacking workouts to get the most out of yourself. I’m here to see where that gets me and to share this journey with fabulous people ❤️
